05527nam a22008535i 9780812205107DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979954213  a97808122051077 a10.9783/97808122051072doi  a(DE-B1597)449451  a(OCoLC)810039396  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041502bisacsh1 aPaige, Nicholas D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBefore Fiction :bThe Ancien Regime of the Novel /cNicholas D. Paige. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b1 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Three Regimes of the Novel -- tChapter 1. The Impossible Princess (Lafayette) -- tChapter 2. Quixote Circa 1670 (Subligny) -- tChapter 3. How to Read a Mind (Crébillon) -- tChapter 4. The Aesthetics of Sentiment (Rousseau) -- tChapter 5. The Demon of Reality (Diderot) -- tChapter 6. Beyond Belief (Cazotte) -- tConclusion: On Narrators Natural and Unnatural -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFiction has become nearly synonymous with literature itself, as if Homer and Dante and Pynchon were all engaged in the same basic activity. But one difficulty with this view is simply that a literature trafficking in openly invented characters is a quite recent development. Novelists before the nineteenth century ceaselessly asserted that their novels were true stories, and before that, poets routinely took their basic plots and heroes from the past. We have grown accustomed to thinking of the history of literature and the novel as a progression from the ideal to the real. Yet paradoxically, the modern triumph of realism is also the triumph of a literature that has shed all pretense to literalness.Before Fiction: The Ancien Régime of the Novel offers a new understanding of the early history of the genre in England and France, one in which writers were not slowly discovering a type of fictionality we now take for granted but rather following a distinct set of practices and rationales. Nicholas D. Paige reinterprets Lafayette's La Princesse de Clèves, Rousseau's Julie, ou la Nouvelle Héloïse, Diderot's La Religieuse, and other French texts of the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries in light of the period's preoccupation with literal truth. Paige argues that novels like these occupied a place before fiction, a pseudofactual realm that in no way leads to modern realism. The book provides an alternate way of looking at a familiar history, and in its very idiom and methodology charts a new course for how we should study the novel and think about the evolution of cultural forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEnglish fictionvThemes, motives. 0aEnglish fictionx17th centuryvThemes, motives. 0aEnglish fictionx18th centuryvThemes, motives. 0aEnglish fictiony17th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aEnglish fictiony18th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aFictionvTechnique. 0aFrench fictionvThemes, motives. 0aFrench fictionx17th centuryvThemes, motives. 0aFrench fictionx18th centuryvThemes, motives. 0aFrench fictiony17th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aFrench fictiony18th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aLITERARY CRITICISMzEuropeanvFrench. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package